\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
\f1\b0\fs32 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri-1\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs20 \cf0 Executive Summary: 
\f1\b0 Bananas and plantains\'a0are staple crops for household consumption and income for smallholder farmers in the humid and sub-humid tropical climate zones across Africa. Plantains make up\'a0\cf3 \ul \ulc3 25%\cf0 \ulnone \'a0of critical dietary carbohydrates for populations across West and Central Africa, amounting to about 70 million people. Bananas and plantains are highly sought after exports in global trade, especially in\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://furtherafrica.com/2022/03/11/the-banana-economy-and-how-it-can-transform-africa/%22%20%5Ct%20%22_blank"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 European markets (}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://furtherafrica.com/2022/03/11/the-banana-economy-and-how-it-can-transform-africa/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 https://furtherafrica.com/2022/03/11/the-banana-economy-and-how-it-can-transform-africa/}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://furtherafrica.com/2022/03/11/the-banana-economy-and-how-it-can-transform-africa/%22%20%5Ct%20%22_blank"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 ),}}\'a0representing a key source of income generation for both individual smallholder farmers and national GDP growth. However, harmful effects of climate change threaten continued economic growth from plantain and banana cultivation, have the potential to deteriorate biodiversity in the tropics, and threaten food security for millions of Africans. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.iita.org/research"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Institute of Tropical Agriculture (IITA)}} has over 50 years of expertise in engineering climate-smart banana technologies and agronomy practices, with grassroots relationships to farmers, ensuring a sustainable solution for the humid and sub-humid tropical zones.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri-1\partightenfactor0

